      "body": "<p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">First, let’s understand </span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">what is fall and spring semester</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> according to the US norms.&nbsp;</span></p><ul><li class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Fall Semester typically starts with the Fall season. Usually most of the school and the universities start in Aug-September marking the start of fall.</span></li><li class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Spring semester starts in January - February marking the incoming spring Semester.&nbsp;</span></li><li class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Summer semester which is the last term is a small break between these two.&nbsp;</span></li></ul><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Now let’s come to the question,</span><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> fall or spring, which semester should you choose?&nbsp;</strong></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The answer to this question firstly depends on the level of College degree you are going for. Are you going for a Bachelor's, Masters or Doctorate/ PHD?</span></p><ul><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Undergrad or PHD Degree</span></li></ul><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">If you are planning to go for either of these, it is recommended going for any of the semesters. It doesn't really matter.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">As an undergrad, it's alright to go for spring semester if you do not want to waste 6 more months.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">If you are planning for a PHD, you are going to work under your professor anyway so whatever you pick, you will have to do 4 to 5 years of research so just go wherever you are getting an opportunity.&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><ul><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Masters Degree</span></li></ul><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Students actually have a lot of trouble in deciding which semester to go for when they are going for masters.</span></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p class=\"ql-align-center\"><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Major reasons why someone would choose fall</strong></p><p><br></p><ol><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Higher number of courses offered in Fall</span></li></ol><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The number of courses offered in Fall are higher as compared to Spring. There are some schools like Carnegie Mellon who don't have spring intake at all. This means you are just narrowing down your choices here.&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><ol><li class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Higher Internship Opportunities&nbsp;</span></li></ol><p><br></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">According to the US - Customs and Immigration Department (USCIS), a F1 student is supposed to complete 2 consecutive semesters in their respective US university to be able to work or apply for CPT which is Curricular Practical Training.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Curricular Practical Training is temporary employment authorization for F-1 visa non-immigrant foreign students in the United States while enrolled in a college-level degree program. </span><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent;\">In simple terms, you can only intern in a company if you have completed at least 9 months or 2 sems of study in a US university.&nbsp;</span></p><p><strong style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">This means for everyone who is going for spring sem, they can not work during summer because of this rule.</strong><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> And that is one major red flag for a lot of students who are looking forward to work.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">But if you want to do research it’s fine if you come for spring. You can work on individual projects under professors which helps you in research.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">If you want to work first you can do an internship, the way you can do a COOP which is an extended internship is by applying in January. And there are limited companies which hire in January.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">But again if you think you didn’t get a good school in Fall, then you should definitely consider spring if you have to have to go. Also you are in some way trading one thing for the other. In this case its internship for time use.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">You can always do summer jobs during summer. Take up your own projects or maybe work in your own country.&nbsp;</span></p><ol><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">Other Benefits</span></li></ol><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">When it comes to assistantship, since a major chunk of students graduate in May a major part of assistantship positions open before fall and that gives a fall intake student chances to apply. Moreover some professors, test and try with students. Which means for the first sem they will hire them as a grader and then offer them an assistantship position.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Drawback with going for Fall-&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Prerequisite courses- A lot of courses offered in spring require prerequisites which are offered during fall. Which means if you can’t take those courses you are not eligible to take the course in spring. </span></p><p><br></p><p><br></p>",
